The Standard Definition of NIL

NIL is an algorithmic language for computer programming.

NIL is used via a Session interface.
The Session is a live process which awaits input from the programmer and will
preserve data and definitions which the programmer constructs throughout their
use of the Session.
The Session relies on a system of Modules to store information between input
from the programmer.
There are three Modules which a Session is required to provide, Default, System,
and Auxiliary.
The Default Module contains all data, syntax, and define declarations which
make up the NIL language.
The System Module provides access to the resources of the host environment.
The System Module is implementation dependent and also host dependent.
The Auxiliary Module contains any implementation defined definitions which are
not directly associated with the host environment, but are still considered
necessary.
The Auxiliary Module is intended to provide implementation dependent, but
otherwise host-independent functionality. Definitions in the Auxiliary Module
cannot be host-dependent, but may still be implementation dependent.

The Session minimally shall provide a duplex stream whereby the programmer will
submit writte Programs to the Session, which will be evaluated upon receipt, and
the Session will yield the written result of that program to the programmer.
A Session may provide any implementation defined user interface as long as this
minimal interface is exposed in some capacity.

The Session can be affected by the following Macros...
(syntax Load (load)
 "Load will accept a Path that points to the location of saved NIL Module.
  Load will convert the saved Module file into a live Module instance.
  Load will function identically to the filesystem macro Read except that it
  yields a live Module instance, rather than a File instance."
  (load path) (((Path) → FileSystem Module) path))

(syntax Save (save)
 "Save will attempt to export a live Module instance to a File in the FileSystem.
  Save will function identically to Write except that it writes a Module to the
  filesystem which can be used by the Load macro.
  Save can be invoked with a specific Module provided by its binding, or with
  only a path in which case Save will write out the Context."
 (save path) (((Module) (Path) → FileSystem _) Context path)
 (save module path) (((Module) (Path) → FileSystem _) module path))

